The vanishing electron mass, $\theta _{12}^{\mathrm {PMNS}}$, and $\theta _{13}^{\mathrm {PMNS}}$ are not accidental. In order to explain this, let us first consider the case of $O(2)$. Since $O(2)$ is a continuous symmetry, there always exists an $O(2)$ transformation that keeps the VEV configuration Eq. (5) invariant, such as
(17) \begin{equation}\label{eq17} \left(\begin{matrix} \cos\theta & \sin\theta \\ \sin\theta &-\cos\theta \end{matrix}\right)=\frac{1}{s_1^2 + s_2^2} \left(\begin{matrix} s_1^2 - s_2^2 & 2s_1s_2 \\ 2s_1s_2 & -(s_1^2 - s_2^2) \end{matrix}\right). \end{equation} 

After the symmetry breaking, this invariance ends up an unbroken $Z_2$ symmetry under which the left-handed leptons transform as
(18) \begin{equation}\label{eq18} L_i \rightarrow \frac{1}{\delta_s^2} \left(\begin{matrix} \delta_1^2 - \delta_2^2 & 2\delta_1\delta_2 & 0 \\ 2\delta_1\delta_2 & -(\delta_1^2 - \delta_2^2) & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & \delta_s^2 \end{matrix}\right)_{ij} L_j, \end{equation} 

or, in the diagonal basis of the charged lepton mass matrix, it becomes
(19) \begin{equation}\label{eq19} L_i \rightarrow\left(\begin{matrix} -1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{matrix}\right)_{ij} L_j. \end{equation} 

From Eq. (19), it is clear that the electron mass, $\theta _{12}^{\mathrm {PMNS}}$, and $\theta _{13}^{\mathrm {PMNS}}$ are forbidden by this $Z_2$ symmetry. Also, looking back at Eqs. (6) and (7), it can be found that they take the most general $Z_2$-invariant forms. In the case of $D_N$, the $Z_2$ symmetry may not be an exact one because $D_N$ is a discrete group. Corrections stemming from this violation, however, are negligibly small as long as the order of $D_N$ is sufficiently large. In the case of $N=9$, for instance, effects of the $Z_2$ breaking appear in $(x/\Lambda _F^7) \bar {L}_I H \ell _{i} (S^7)_I$ for the first time. A $D_9$-invariant term is obtained by constructing $\textbf {2}_2$ from $(S^7)_I$ via $\textbf {2}_3 \otimes \textbf {2}_4$ with the tensor product Eq. (4). After $S_{1,2}$ develop VEVs, the resultant term violates the $Z_2$ symmetry and induces a non-zero but negligibly small electron mass. Similarly, the breaking effects in the neutrino sector are ignorable. If $N \le 7$, it may be possible to reproduce a realistic electron mass. Although this is an interesting idea, we will discuss a different breaking mechanism of $Z_2$ in the next section while assuming $N \ge 9$. Note that the $Z_2$ symmetry originates in the parity included in $D_N$ and $O(2)$, whereas $SO(2)$ does not include it.

One way to break the $Z_2$ symmetry is to promote $S_{I}$ to complex scalars with complex VEVs. In the current and subsequent subsections, just for simplicity, we assume that all the dimensionless couplings are real and invoke spontaneous CP violation (SCPV). The availability of SCPV will be discussed in the next subsection, and here we simply rewrite the VEVs of the scalars as
(20)  egin{equation}\label{eq20} \langle H angle=v,\quad \langle S_I angle=(s_1 e^{i\phi_1}\ s_2 e^{i\phi_2})^T. \end{equation} 

As can be seen from Eq. (17), an unbroken limit of the $Z_2$ symmetry corresponds to $\phi _1 = \phi _2$, which keeps the right-hand side real, and thus a slight splitting between them is expected to trigger a non-zero electron mass, $	heta _{12}^{\mathrm {PMNS}}$, and $	heta _{13}^{m PMNS}$. The Lagrangian is augmented by the following new terms:
