$D_N$ is a group of a discrete rotation, $R$, and a parity, $P$, in the 2D plane, and their 2D matrix representations are given by (A1) \begin{equation}\label{eqA1} R^q= \left(\begin{matrix} \cos\dfrac{2\pi}{N}q & \sin\dfrac{2\pi}{N}q \\ -\sin\dfrac{2\pi}{N}q & \cos\dfrac{2\pi}{N}q \end{matrix}\right),\quad P=\left(\begin{matrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 &-1 \end{matrix}\right), \end{equation}
where $q=1, \ldots , N-1$ is an integer. It can be inferred from $R^N=1$ and $P^2=1$ that $D_N$ contains $Z_N$ and $Z_2$ as subgroups. There are $2N$ group elements: \[ {\mathcal G}=1,R,R^2, \ldots, R^{N-1},P,PR,PR^2, \ldots, PR^{N-1}, \]
and the number of irreducible representations is \begin{align*} &\frac{N-2}{2}\hbox{ doublets plus }4\hbox{ singlets for }N={\mathrm{even}}, \\ &\frac{N-1}{2}\hbox{ doublets plus }2 \hbox{ singlets for }N={\rm odd}. \end{align*}
In what follows, we concentrate on the case of $N={\mathrm { odd}}$. See Refs. [13,14] for the $N={\mathrm {even}}$ case.

The tensor products between the singlets are
(A2) \begin{equation}\label{eqA2} \textbf{1}^\prime \otimes \textbf{1}^\prime = \textbf{1},\quad\textbf{1} \otimes \textbf{1}^\prime = \textbf{1}^\prime, \end{equation} 

and those between the doublets are
(A3) \begin{align} &\begin{array}{ccccccccc} \left(\begin{matrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{matrix}\right) & \otimes & \left(\begin{matrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \end{matrix}\right) & = & (x_1y_1+x_2y_2) & \oplus & (x_1y_2-x_2y_1) & \oplus & \left(\begin{matrix} x_1y_1-x_2y_2 \\ x_1y_2+x_2y_1 \end{matrix}\right) \nonumber \\ \textbf{2}_n & \otimes & \textbf{2}_n & = & \textbf{1} & \oplus & \textbf{1}^\prime & \oplus & \textbf{2}_{2n} \end{array},\nonumber \\ &\begin{array}{ccccccc} \left(\begin{matrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{matrix}\right) & \otimes & \left(\begin{matrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \end{matrix}\right) & = & \left(\begin{matrix} x_1y_1+x_2y_2 \\ x_1y_2-x_2y_1 \end{matrix}\right) & \oplus & \left(\begin{matrix} x_1y_1-x_2y_2 \\ x_1y_2+x_2y_1 \end{matrix}\right) \label{eqA3}\\ \textbf{2}_n & \otimes & \textbf{2}_{m >n} & = & \textbf{2}_{m-n} & \oplus & \textbf{2}_{m+n} \end{array} \end{align} 

if $2n \le (N-1)/2$ and $n+m \le (N-1)/2$, while
(A4) \begin{align} &\begin{array}{ccccccccc} \left(\begin{matrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{matrix}\right) & \otimes & \left(\begin{matrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \end{matrix}\right) & = & (x_1y_1+x_2y_2) & \oplus & (x_1y_2-x_2y_1) & \oplus & \left(\begin{matrix} -x_1y_1+x_2y_2 \\ x_1y_2+x_2y_1 \end{matrix}\right) \nonumber \\ \textbf{2}_n & \otimes & \textbf{2}_n & = & \textbf{1} & \oplus & \textbf{1}^\prime & \oplus & \textbf{2}_{N-2n} \end{array},\nonumber \\ &\begin{array}{ccccccc} \left(\begin{matrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \end{matrix}\right) & \otimes & \left(\begin{matrix} y_1 \\ y_2 \end{matrix}\right) & = & \left(\begin{matrix} x_1y_1+x_2y_2 \\ x_1y_2-x_2y_1 \end{matrix}\right) & \oplus & \left(\begin{matrix} -x_1y_1+x_2y_2 \\ x_1y_2+x_2y_1 \end{matrix}\right) \label{eqA4} \\ \textbf{2}_n & \otimes & \textbf{2}_{m >n} & = & \textbf{2}_{m-n} & \oplus & \textbf{2}_{N-(m+n)} \end{array} \end{align} 

if $2n >(N-1)/2$ and $n+m >(N-1)/2$. Note that Eqs. (A2) and (A3) are the same as those of $O(2)$, whereas Eq. (A4) is used only for $D_N$.

$O(2)$ is a group of a continuous rotation and a parity in the 2D plane:
(B1) \begin{align}\label{eqB1} R^q=\left(\begin{matrix} \cos\theta q & \sin\theta q \\ -\sin\theta q & \cos\theta q \end{matrix}\right),\quad P= \left(\begin{matrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 &-1 \end{matrix}\right), \end{align} 

where $\theta $ is a continuous parameter. There exist two singlets, $\textbf {1}$ and $\textbf {1}^\prime $ like $D_N$, and an infinite number of doublets. The doublets can be labeled with the integer $q$, such as $\textbf {2}_1$, $\textbf {2}_2, \ldots .$ The tensor products are the same as Eqs. (A2) and (A3) for all doublets.
